content.content:
1	---
2	name: waiting-for-codex-review
3	description: Use immediately after pushing a PR to GitHub when Codex is configured to review the branch. Codex reviews asynchronously — it leaves a 👀 reaction on the PR while reviewing, and a 👍 reaction when satisfied. This skill defines the polling loop and the response workflow: wait for Codex to react, address any review threads it posts with the same rigor as `post-implementation-audit` (TDD + no coverage regression), commit, push, reply inline, resolve the thread, then keep waiting until 👍. Triggers on phrases like "wait for codex review", "what does codex say", "is codex done", "address the codex feedback", "check the PR reviews", or any post-push handoff where the user expects an automated reviewer's verdict. Invoke this skill even when the user does not explicitly name Codex — any GitHub PR where a 👀/👍 reaction signals an automated reviewer follows the same pattern.
4	---
5	
6	# Waiting for Codex Review
7	
8	Codex (the OpenAI Codex automated reviewer) reviews open PRs asynchronously. The contract is:
9	
10	- **Run starts** → Codex adds a 👀 (eyes) reaction to the PR.
11	- **Approved** → Codex adds a 👍 (thumbsup) reaction to the PR. No further action required.
12	- **Changes requested** → Codex posts one or more inline review threads. 👀 typically stays until the next run completes after your fix.
13	
14	This skill is the polling + response loop for that contract. You stay in it until 👍 lands.
15	
16	## When to invoke
17	
18	Invoke as soon as a PR is pushed and Codex is set up for the repository. Common trigger phrases:
19	
20	- "wait for the codex review"
21	- "what does codex say about the PR"
22	- "address the codex feedback"
23	- "check the PR reviews"
24	- "is codex still reviewing"
25	
26	If the user pushes a PR and gives no explicit next instruction, default to invoking this skill — the right next step is to watch for Codex.
27	
28	## Reaction lookups: the exact data
29	
30	PRs are issues for the reactions endpoint. The bot's login depends on the install — on installs that use the ChatGPT Codex connector it's `chatgpt-codex-connector`; on the standalone Codex Cloud install it may be `codex[bot]` or similar. The first poll of this loop **discovers the bot login** rather than hard-coding it: any review-comment author whose handle contains `codex` is treated as Codex.
31	
32	```bash
33	# Reactions on the PR itself
34	gh api repos/<owner>/<repo>/issues/<pr>/reactions
35	# → array of { user.login, content } where content ∈ {'+1','-1','laugh','confused','heart','hooray','rocket','eyes'}
36	# +1 == 👍, eyes == 👀
37	
38	# Reviews and review threads
39	gh pr view <pr> --json reviews
40	gh api graphql -f query='
41	  query($owner:String!,$repo:String!,$n:Int!){
42	    repository(owner:$owner,name:$repo){
43	      pullRequest(number:$n){
44	        reviewThreads(first:100){
45	          nodes{
46	            id            # GraphQL node id — use this to RESOLVE
47	            isResolved
48	            comments(first:100){
49	              nodes{ databaseId author{login} path line body }
50	              # databaseId is the REST id — use this to REPLY
51	            }
52	          }
53	        }
54	      }
55	    }
56	  }' -F owner=<owner> -F repo=<repo> -F n=<pr>
57	```
58	
59	Keep two ids per thread straight: **`thread.id`** (GraphQL node id, opaque string starting with `PRRT_...`) is needed to *resolve* the thread; **`comment.databaseId`** (integer) is needed to *reply* in-line. They are not interchangeable.
60	
61	## The loop
62	
63	```dot
64	digraph codex_loop {
